{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"700cce57-55ed-4191-8c53-80f3e49f94bb","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Blocked by bug #123\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\n> **Note:** In xUnit, `Skip` is a property on the test attribute itself, not a separate attribute. For NUnit and MSTest, the attribute name is the same (`Ignore`) but they come from different namespaces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c05491e3-8290-482d-b8c1-6831c46a9121","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without tools.","outputTokens":329,"requestId":"4819:2AD648:797291:8BDD51:69FBE745"},"id":"57941f77-dcaa-4aea-94cc-6c60a892fb50","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:13:47.973Z","parentId":"8aa48f61-9a3f-4d43-bc2a-a936e289d4a7"}
